Elliotte,

What would you expect the test runner to do if it caught one of these 
exceptions?  In general, I would expect that listeners should not 
interrupt the test execution: if they find themselves unable to do what 
they want, they should quietly deal with it on their own.

    David Saff

Elliotte Rusty Harold wrote:

&gt; I&#39;m trying to implement a custom TestListener in JUnit 4. These methods
&gt; do I/O. They tend to look like this:
&gt;
&gt;      public void testRunStarted(int testCount) {
&gt;          try {
&gt;              out.write(&quot;&lt;?xml version=&#39;1.0&#39; encoding=&#39;UTF-8&#39;?&gt;&#92;r&#92;n&quot;);
&gt;          }
&gt;          catch (IOException ex) {
&gt;              throw new RuntimeException(ex);
&gt;          }
&gt;      }
&gt;
&gt; Should the TestListener interfaces be declared to throw Exception or
&gt; some kind of JUnitException so one doesn&#39;t have to wrap everything in a
&gt; RuntimeException?
